# Internationalization (i18n) Rules

## Lingui
- Use Lingui (`@lingui/core`, `@lingui/react`) for all internationalization
- Wrap app with `LinguiProvider` from `app/providers/LinguiProvider`
- Use `Trans` component for complex translations with HTML
- Use `t` macro for simple string translations

## Translation Files
- Translation files are in `@locales/` directory
- Support languages: `en` (English), `uk` (Ukrainian)
- Each language has `messages.ts` file
- Use `npm run translations:extract` to extract translatable strings
- Use `npm run translations:compile` to compile translations

## Usage Patterns
- Use `t` macro for simple strings: `t`Hello World``
- Use `Trans` component for strings with HTML: `<Trans>Hello <strong>World</strong></Trans>`
- Use `plural` for pluralization
- Use `select` for gender/conditional translations

## Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive keys for translation strings
- Group related translations together
- Use namespacing for large features (e.g., `auth.login`, `request.create`)

## Best Practices
- Always extract strings for translation, never hardcode user-facing text
- Test UI in both languages
- Keep translations context-aware
- Use interpolation for dynamic values: `t`Hello {name}`` with `name` variable

## Code Examples
```typescript
// Simple translation
import { t } from '@lingui/macro';
const message = t`Welcome`;

// Component with translation
import { Trans } from '@lingui/react';
<Trans>Click <button>here</button> to continue</Trans>

// With variables
import { t } from '@lingui/macro';
const message = t`Hello ${userName}`;
```
